comments.body:
@Luap99 
> Just start the specific container then? `podman start xxx-infra` should be enough.

That's a way to go, a little hacky though since it does not hide the implementation details from a user ...

@rhatdan 
> You want to create a Pod with containers that are not running at start? That is a new behaviour? Could you just add and remove the containers from the Pod when you want them to start and stop?

It sound like a bit heavy operation (at least on surface). It's better to do it at the configuration level, I think ...
